Not an unheard-of problem with these carbines.If I find time I'll run through it and see if I can resolve the problem, in the meantime the price is dirt cheap!
Built by National Ordnance in So Cal, this is an M1 carbine, ser# 79xx in nice overall shape.  These were produced in the sixties after the patents on the military M1 carbine expired, and were sold to the public as well as law enforcement agencies, and foreign governments. The low wood potbelly  stock with a ventilated handguard has an isolated 1 inch crack under the buttplate (pictured) which is separated by the sling/oiler cutout, and does not effect the rest of the stock.  The solid front sight with no holes in the uprights dates this rifle  to post-1965 from what I've read.  Due to California law the 15 round magazine isn't included with the carbine unless you are a LEO or have an out-of-state address I can ship it to, however 10 round mags are available on the market. The 18" barrel has a nice looking mirror bore with six groove rifling.  This has the correct longer inertia block on the front of the slide (pictured), not the problematic shorter versions that some of the later models had. title: For Sale:  1830's Belgian Double Barrel Cap and Ball Muzzleloader Pistol 32 cal
postcontent:
Still fires, takes about ten grains. Hairline crack on trigger box(does not affect integrity). Overall good shape tight barrel seal.

This is a 1830's Belgian pistol that would be described as "bag-butt, screw barrels.
The shape of the hand-grip, like a cloth bag or " even a bull's scrotum, makes the term "bag-butt" appropriate.
The four notches you see in the muzzle of each barrel fit a wrench which came with the gun (now long lost). With the wrench, you could unscrew the barrels individually. Removing a barrel would present you with a hollow, tube-like chamber into which you would pour a measure of black powder, which would then be topped by a round ball.
The length of the inner chamber would automatically limit the amount of powder you could put into it, and its interior diameter would limit the diameter of the (soft lead) ball. Thus, a safe charge was guaranteed.

I'm Asking $150 or best reasonable offer Call or Text at 414.588/0077
